This lemma states that an empty path (with a single vertex $x$) is an alternating path if and only if $x$ is in the vertex set of the graph. This is trivially true by the definition of an alternating path.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.of_cons (h : G.IsAltPath hM (.cons x e P)) : G.IsAltPath hM P := by
  simp only [isAltPath_iff, cons_isPath_iff, WList.cons_edge] at h ⊢
  obtain ⟨⟨hP, hl, hx⟩, he⟩ := h
  exact ⟨hP, he.of_cons⟩
```

This lemma states that if we have an alternating path starting with a specific vertex $x$ and edge $e$, then the rest of the path is also an alternating path. This follows from the definition of an alternating path and the fact that the property is preserved when removing the first vertex and edge.

```tactics
@[simp]
lemma IsAltPath.tail (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) : G.IsAltPath hM P.tail := by
  match P with
  | .nil u => simp_all
  | .cons u e w => simp [h.of_cons]
```

This lemma states that if $P$ is an alternating path, then the path obtained by removing the first vertex and edge is also an alternating path. This is true because the definition of an alternating path is preserved by taking the tail.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.suffix (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) (h' : P'.IsSuffix P) : G.IsAltPath hM P' :=
  h'.recOfTail (fun _ h ↦ h.tail) h
```

This lemma states that if $P$ is an alternating path and $P'$ is a suffix of $P$, then $P'$ is also an alternating path. This follows from the fact that taking a suffix of an alternating path preserves the alternating property.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.of_concat (h : G.IsAltPath hM (P.concat e x)) : G.IsAltPath hM P := by
  simp only [isAltPath_iff, concat_isPath_iff, WList.concat_edge, List.isChain_append,
    List.IsChain.singleton, Option.mem_def, List.head?_cons, Option.some.injEq, forall_eq',
    true_and] at h ⊢
  obtain ⟨⟨hP, hl, hx⟩, he, hlast⟩ := h
  refine ⟨hP, he⟩
```

This lemma states that if $P$ is an alternating path and we concatenate it with another edge $e$ and vertex $x$, then the resulting path is also an alternating path. This is true because the alternating property is preserved under concatenation.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.dropLast (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) : G.IsAltPath hM P.dropLast := by
  obtain ⟨v, rfl⟩ | hne := P.exists_eq_nil_or_nonempty
  · rwa [WList.dropLast_nil]
  obtain ⟨w', f, y, rfl⟩ := hne.exists_concat
  rw [WList.dropLast_concat]
  exact h.of_concat
```

This lemma states that if $P$ is an alternating path, then the path obtained by removing the last vertex is also an alternating path. This is true because taking the dropLast of an alternating path preserves the alternating property.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.prefix (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) (h' : P'.IsPrefix P) : G.IsAltPath hM P' :=
  h'.recOfDropLast (fun _ h ↦ h.dropLast) h
```

This lemma states that if $P$ is an alternating path and $P'$ is a prefix of $P$, then $P'$ is also an alternating path. This follows from the fact that taking a prefix of an alternating path preserves the alternating property.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.mem_matching_iff {P : WList α β} (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) :
    P.edge.IsChain (fun e f ↦ e ∈ M ↔ f ∉ M) := by
  match P with
  | .nil u => simp
  | .cons u e (.nil v) => simp
  | .cons u e (.cons v f w) =>
    simp only [WList.cons_edge, List.isChain_cons_cons]
    obtain ⟨hor, -⟩ := by simpa using h.mem_matching
    obtain ⟨⟨hef, -⟩, -, -⟩ := by simpa using h.isTrail.edge_nodup
    obtain ⟨⟨-, hfvwf, -⟩, heuv, -, -⟩ := by simpa using h.toIsPath
    use ⟨fun heM hfM ↦ ?_, hor.resolve_right⟩, by simpa using h.of_cons.mem_matching_iff
    exact hM.disjoint heM hfM hef |>.notMem_of_mem_left heuv.inc_right hfvwf.inc_left
```

This lemma provides a characterization of the membership condition for edges in the matching $M$ along the path $P$. It states that the edges of $P$ form a chain where an edge is in $M$ if and only if the next edge is not in $M$.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.mem_matching_iff' {P : WList α β} (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) :
    P.edge.IsChain (fun e f ↦ e ∉ M ↔ f ∈ M) := by
  convert h.mem_matching_iff using 3
  rw [iff_not_comm, iff_comm (a := _ ∈ M)]
```

This lemma is similar to the previous one but with the membership condition flipped. It states that the edges of $P$ form a chain where an edge is in $M$ if and only if the next edge is not in $M$.

